#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Discover how to configure compilers in Spack, whether by specifying them as "
"externals, or by installing them with Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:13
msgid "Configuring Compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:15
msgid ""
"Spack has the ability to build packages with multiple compilers and compiler "
"versions. Compilers can be made available to Spack by:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:18
msgid "Specifying them as externals in ``packages.yaml``, or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:19
msgid "Having them installed in the current Spack store, or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:20
msgid "Having them available as binaries in a build cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:22
msgid ""
"For convenience, Spack will automatically detect compilers as externals the "
"first time it needs them, if no compiler is available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:27
msgid "``spack compiler list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:29
msgid ""
"You can see which compilers are available to Spack by running ``spack "
"compiler list``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:31
msgid ""
"$ spack compiler list\n"
"==> Available compilers\n"
"-- gcc ubuntu20.04-x86_64 ---------------------------------------\n"
"[e]  gcc@10.5.0  [+]  gcc@15.1.0  [+]  gcc@14.3.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:38
msgid ""
"Compilers marked with an ``[e]`` are system compilers (externals), and those "
"marked with a ``[+]`` have been installed by Spack. Compilers from remote "
"build caches are marked as ``-``, but are not shown by default. To see them "
"you need a specific option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:42
msgid ""
"$ spack compiler list --remote\n"
"==> Available compilers\n"
"-- gcc ubuntu20.04-x86_64 ---------------------------------------\n"
"[e]  gcc@10.5.0  [+]  gcc@15.1.0  [+]  gcc@14.3.0\n"
"\n"
"-- gcc ubuntu20.04-x86_64 ---------------------------------------\n"
" -   gcc@12.4.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:52
msgid ""
"Any of these compilers can be used to build Spack packages. More details on "
"how this is done can be found in :ref:`sec-specs`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:58
msgid "``spack compiler find``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:60
msgid "If you do not see a compiler in the list shown by:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:62
msgid "$ spack compiler list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:66
msgid ""
"but you want to use it with Spack, you can simply run ``spack compiler "
"find`` with the path to where the compiler is installed. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:69
msgid ""
"$ spack compiler find /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/2025.1/bin/\n"
"==> Added 1 new compiler to /home/user/.spack/packages.yaml\n"
"    intel-oneapi-compilers@2025.1.0\n"
"==> Compilers are defined in the following files:\n"
"    /home/user/.spack/packages.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:77
msgid ""
"Or you can run ``spack compiler find`` with no arguments to force auto-"
"detection. This is useful if you do not know where compilers are installed, "
"but you know that new compilers have been added to your ``PATH``. For "
"example, you might load a module, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:81
msgid ""
"$ module load gcc/4.9.0\n"
"$ spack compiler find\n"
"==> Added 1 new compiler to /home/user/.spack/packages.yaml\n"
"    gcc@4.9.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:88
msgid ""
"This loads the environment module for gcc-4.9.0 to add it to ``PATH``, and "
"then it adds the compiler to Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:92
msgid ""
"By default, Spack does not fill in the ``modules:`` field in the ``packages."
"yaml`` file. If you are using a compiler from a module, then you should add "
"this field manually. See the section on :ref:`compilers-requiring-modules`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:99
msgid "``spack compiler info``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:101
msgid ""
"If you want to see additional information about specific compilers, you can "
"run ``spack compiler info``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:103
msgid ""
"$ spack compiler info gcc\n"
"gcc@=8.4.0 languages='c,c++,fortran' arch=linux-ubuntu20.04-x86_64:\n"
"  prefix: /usr\n"
"  compilers:\n"
"    c: /usr/bin/gcc-8\n"
"    cxx: /usr/bin/g++-8\n"
"    fortran: /usr/bin/gfortran-8\n"
"\n"
"gcc@=9.4.0 languages='c,c++,fortran' arch=linux-ubuntu20.04-x86_64:\n"
"  prefix: /usr\n"
"  compilers:\n"
"    c: /usr/bin/gcc\n"
"    cxx: /usr/bin/g++\n"
"    fortran: /usr/bin/gfortran\n"
"\n"
"gcc@=10.5.0 languages='c,c++,fortran' arch=linux-ubuntu20.04-x86_64:\n"
"  prefix: /usr\n"
"  compilers:\n"
"    c: /usr/bin/gcc-10\n"
"    cxx: /usr/bin/g++-10\n"
"    fortran: /usr/bin/gfortran-10"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:127
msgid ""
"This shows the details of the compilers that were detected by Spack. Notice "
"also that we didn't have to be too specific about the version. We just said "
"``gcc``, and we got information about all the matching compilers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:132
msgid "Manual configuration of external compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:134
msgid ""
"If auto-detection fails, you can manually configure a compiler by editing "
"your ``packages`` configuration. You can do this by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:137
msgid "$ spack config edit packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:141
msgid ""
"which will open the file in :ref:`your favorite editor <controlling-the-"
"editor>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:143
msgid ""
"Each compiler has an \"external\" entry in the file with "
"``extra_attributes``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:145
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  gcc:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: gcc@10.5.0 languages='c,c++,fortran'\n"
"      prefix: /usr\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        compilers:\n"
"          c: /usr/bin/gcc-10\n"
"          cxx: /usr/bin/g++-10\n"
"          fortran: /usr/bin/gfortran-10"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:158
msgid ""
"The compiler executables are listed under ``extra_attributes:compilers``, "
"and are keyed by language. Once you save the file, the configured compilers "
"will show up in the list displayed by ``spack compilers``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:161
msgid ""
"You can also add compiler flags to manually configured compilers. These "
"flags should be specified in the ``flags`` section of the compiler "
"specification. The valid flags are ``cflags``, ``cxxflags``, ``fflags``, "
"``cppflags``, ``ldflags``, and ``ldlibs``. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:166
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  gcc:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: gcc@10.5.0 languages='c,c++,fortran'\n"
"      prefix: /usr\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        compilers:\n"
"          c: /usr/bin/gcc-10\n"
"          cxx: /usr/bin/g++-10\n"
"          fortran: /usr/bin/gfortran-10\n"
"        flags:\n"
"          cflags: -O3 -fPIC\n"
"          cxxflags: -O3 -fPIC\n"
"          cppflags: -O3 -fPIC"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:183
msgid ""
"These flags will be treated by Spack as if they were entered from the "
"command line each time this compiler is used. The compiler wrappers then "
"inject those flags into the compiler command. Compiler flags entered from "
"the command line will be discussed in more detail in the following section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:187
msgid ""
"Some compilers also require additional environment configuration. Examples "
"include Intel's oneAPI and AMD's AOCC compiler suites, which have custom "
"scripts for loading environment variables and setting paths. These variables "
"should be specified in the ``environment`` section of the compiler "
"specification. The operations available to modify the environment are "
"``set``, ``unset``, ``prepend_path``, ``append_path``, and ``remove_path``. "
"For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:193
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  intel-oneapi-compilers:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: intel-oneapi-compilers@2025.1.0\n"
"      prefix: /opt/intel/oneapi\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        compilers:\n"
"          c: /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/2025.1/bin/icx\n"
"          cxx: /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/2025.1/bin/icpx\n"
"          fortran: /opt/intel/oneapi/compiler/2025.1/bin/ifx\n"
"        environment:\n"
"          set:\n"
"            MKL_ROOT: \"/path/to/mkl/root\"\n"
"          unset: # A list of environment variables to unset\n"
"          - CC\n"
"          prepend_path: # Similar for append|remove_path\n"
"            LD_LIBRARY_PATH: /ld/paths/added/by/setvars/sh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:213
msgid ""
"It is also possible to specify additional ``RPATHs`` that the compiler will "
"add to all executables generated by that compiler. This is useful for "
"forcing certain compilers to RPATH their own runtime libraries so that "
"executables will run without the need to set ``LD_LIBRARY_PATH``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:216
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  gcc:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: gcc@4.9.3\n"
"      prefix: /opt/gcc\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        compilers:\n"
"          c: /opt/gcc/bin/gcc\n"
"          cxx: /opt/gcc/bin/g++\n"
"          fortran: /opt/gcc/bin/gfortran\n"
"        extra_rpaths:\n"
"        - /path/to/some/compiler/runtime/directory\n"
"        - /path/to/some/other/compiler/runtime/directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:235
msgid "Compilers Requiring Modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:237
msgid ""
"Many installed compilers will work regardless of the environment from which "
"they are called. However, some installed compilers require environment "
"variables to be set in order to run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:240
msgid ""
"On typical HPC clusters, these environment modifications are usually "
"delegated to some \"module\" system. In such a case, you should tell Spack "
"which module(s) to load in order to run the chosen compiler:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:243
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  gcc:\n"
"    externals:\n"
"    - spec: gcc@10.5.0 languages='c,c++,fortran'\n"
"      prefix: /opt/compilers\n"
"      extra_attributes:\n"
"        compilers:\n"
"          c: /opt/compilers/bin/gcc-10\n"
"          cxx: /opt/compilers/bin/g++-10\n"
"          fortran: /opt/compilers/bin/gfortran-10\n"
"      modules: [gcc/10.5.0]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:257
msgid ""
"Some compilers require special environment settings to be loaded not just to "
"run, but also to execute the code they build, breaking packages that need to "
"execute code they just compiled. If it's not possible or practical to use a "
"better compiler, you'll need to ensure that environment settings are "
"preserved for compilers like this (i.e., you'll need to load the module or "
"source the compiler's shell script)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:260
msgid ""
"By default, Spack tries to ensure that builds are reproducible by cleaning "
"the environment before building. If this interferes with your compiler "
"settings, you CAN use ``spack install --dirty`` as a workaround. Note that "
"this MAY interfere with package builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:265
msgid "Build Your Own Compiler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:267
msgid ""
"If you require a specific compiler and version, you can have Spack build it "
"for you. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:270
msgid "$ spack install gcc@14"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:274
msgid ""
"Once the compiler is installed, you can start using it without additional "
"configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:276
msgid "$ spack install hdf5~mpi %gcc@14"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:281
msgid "Mixing Compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:283
msgid ""
"For more options on configuring Spack to mix different compilers for "
"different languages, see :ref:`the toolchains configuration docs "
"<toolchains>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:285
msgid ""
"To disable mixing (e.g. if you have multiple compilers defined, but want "
"each concretized DAG to use one of them consistently), you can set:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:287
msgid ""
"concretizer:\n"
"  compiler_mixing: false"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:292
msgid ""
"This affects root specs and any (transitive) link or run dependencies. Build-"
"only dependencies are allowed to use different compilers (even when this is "
"set)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:295
msgid ""
"Some packages are difficult to build with high performance compilers, and it "
"may be necessary to enable compiler mixing just for those packages. To "
"enable mixing for specific packages, specify an allow-list in the "
"``compiler_mixing`` config:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:298
msgid ""
"concretizer:\n"
"  compiler_mixing: [\"openssl\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../configuring_compilers.rst:303
msgid ""
"Adding ``openssl`` to the compiler mixing allow-list does not allow mixing "
"for dependencies of ``openssl``."
msgstr ""
